Day 44 vending in AZ. Yes, I’ve seen a lot in this timeframe. From museum pieces to broken dreams, Arizona tends to deliver every year. Although my show has been the best ever, I’ve seen a lot of folks not have the best of shows. I keep telling myself to stay in the moment and focus on yourself, but it’s hard when people have a hard time making a living on the mineral trade. This profession isn’t for the overly attached or weak minded. It takes years of dedication through trial and error to find out not only what works, but what you love. Today I sign in to the TGMS show downtown in the convention center and tomorrow is set up. All the hard work has paid off, let’s just see how much. Cheers and blessings from Tucson.
Day 45 of vending in Tucson 🍵🏜💎🔥 As one show ends, another begins. Cheers, blessings, and best intentions. #fireagate #herkimerdiamond

One of the many #fireagate #bead #pipes I have made over the years. I don’t smoke like I use to, but it makes it all the better when your pipe doesn’t break, follows you wherever you go, is concealable, and inconspicuous. 

Being an artist is fun, but it also comes with lots of invested time, internal struggles, financial insecurity, and reaching out to the public without selling out by doing something you don’t want to do. I haven’t done any custom work in years now and hope to keep it that way. Not that I’m against it, I just want to stay on my path. 

This post is a thank you to all the people who have supported me over the years. Thank you for the support.

Thank you to everyone who keeps up with me on this platform. I’m shown that between 8-30 million people tune into some part of my life on this platform every month in over 80+ countries all around the world. I’m figuring it out as I go and plan to post just as much random stuff moving forward until I quit this platform all together at some point. Blessings and stay warm by the fire 🔥🔥

Well, I’ve been trying to get off PayPal for the last few years as I’ve been using another platform that accepts online transactions/payments. This morning I got this message from PP and I called them to see if I could get the remaining money in my account sooner than 180 days: no dice. They told me someone reported me and that’s why they have chosen to permanently delete my business account. When I look to see if any open cases have been opened against me for refunds, it says none have opened up. This being said I am probably no longer able to accept international transactions and I will look into other payment platforms (other than the one I currently use) to try and make things convenient for the people who continue to support me. This is pretty inconvenient for me as the funds I had in my account were going to pay for my bills of this coming month. Okay.. so here is one of the most educational stones where I can explain to people how I “grade” fire agate. The first and most important part of pricing a fire agate is “brightness”. By this I mean how vivid or bright in the stone showing/reflecting light. The beginning of this video shows an extremely bright stone which I value higher than the final outcome. You can see in the second clip the stone is becoming “duller” in brightness but it is because I’m chasing another color. Second in grading a stone, I look at color. The color in the last clip is the best, but the brightness is not nearly as good as the first clip. This all comes into play when I’m cutting fire agate and wondering how much I should risk. Third most important factor in “grading” or pricing a stone is size. These three things are the leading factors in grading fire agates. 

Traditionally, the 4 C’s are used to grade cut gemstones. Color, carat, cut, and clarity. Clarity has no value in fire agate as it’s opaque.

This is the second time I’ve gotten to see this piece in person and it invoked the same feeling inside of me as before, pure astonishment. 
In 1977, Ailton Barbosa began digging for tourmaline on land leased from Jonas Lima. After 6 months of pretty much getting skunked, Lima pretty much threw in the towel, but Barbosa persisted. His crew found a pink-capped black tourmaline pocket where water started pouring down from the ceiling, hinting at another potential pocket directly above. Barbosa had to sell his car in order to get more dynamite and food on one last effort to hit it big. Sure enough, he hit the Bambúrro Pocket which was a 10 foot hollow cavity with the infamous cranberry red tourmaline with snow-white albite and Quartz inside. This specific crystal from the pocket was named “Tarugo” and remains one of the biggest colored tourmaline crystals of this quality to ever be discovered. 
I can only imagine the feeling of uncovering this after digging that long and throwing in all on the line. 

Truly epic 🍒💄🍄

After several sessions, I realized I began to learn more about the people around me. So, I drank more tea to try and understand why people are the way they are. Why people are politically motivated, why people are self-centered, why people are emotional, why people are hurting, why people are confused, why people are desperate for attention, why people want love, why people insult others, why people see things differently, and ultimately what drives people. Although drinking tea has been a huge introspection in my life, it has given me equal knowledge of the outside world. I try to share this with people in many different ways but it’s best to explain it around a tea pouring. In the end, I’m not perfect but I can pour a perfect cup of tea. I got arrested for wearing this hat. I walked all over downtown Nevada City, CA for a day and apparently they didn’t like the fact I was free and letting the world know it. It was near St. Patties day. I had started off my day with a Chai Tea at the Curly Wolf which no longer exists. I asked the barista if I could walk around town and bring the cup back in 5-10 minutes and being a regular she said sure no problem. I walked by Utopian Stone and stood there for a minute. I walked inside and asked to see their Kimberley Reports on any of their diamonds. They told me they didn’t have any. I told them they had blood diamonds then. They told me they get all of them in San Francisco. I asked where and they wouldn’t tell me, so again I stated they had conflict diamonds and walked outside. I then stood outside, sipping my tea and began to tell people as they passed by that this place sells blood diamonds. The owner didn’t like that too much and called the cops on me. Cop wasn’t too happy when he came to see me. He demanded my ID and told me I was stealing dishes from storefronts. I told him I had permission and he didn’t like that too much either. So, when I told him this was my town he got livid and pretty much violated my rights. He backed me up against the wall and took my free hand and forced it behind my back. As I wasn’t trying to start anything, I told him my ID was in my wallet. He grabbed my wallet and let my hand go. He basically told me to get out of town or else there would be trouble. I told him I had no where to go as I had just gotten kicked out of my studio because it was raining on me indoors (another story another day). He gave me my ID back and told me I had better leave town. I went back to the Curly Wolf, returned my dish and walked around town some more. I ended up walking into a store and buying this hat. I remember walking by the Crazy Horse and saying “Crazy Hoe” rather loud but not shouting it in any way. After meeting up with @paizleyyy , we walked into McGees. As we walked in, two cops were walking out. We order a drink and and sat down.
May your cup be filled with love and peace 🍵

When I was 27 I learned a few things; one of which was the people you know and call your friends for over 10+ years can leave you in the gutter and try to curb stomp your face in. 
I had just gotten back from the Tucson Gem Show pretty hyped and inspired when everyone told me I needed help. Long story shorter, I flew home to talk with my parents about what transpired. I told them I really wanted to go to Kentucky and find an agate where I had spread my fathers ashes, Roaring Paunch Creek. I parked at the bridge and went upstream. I hiked a few miles and found some uncanny objects. I came to a big open pool with a gentle waterfall and found a shirt. I found some sandals, batteries, film in a bottle, and other things. They were all my fathers. I found some cans of salmon and cracked them open and ate them. My father fed my 7 years after he died right there by that swimming hole. I kept walking downstream and came across a knife edge ravine that I decided to walk across. After that, it was near impossible to turn around so I just kept walking. I came to some railroad tracks and followed them through the woods. I came to a little abandoned town. I went in the main store and no one was around. I walked behind the table where people check out and found a bottle of moonshine. I took it, along with other items I thought I might need being deep in the woods. I even left a note with my phone number letting whoever know I would compensate them. After leaving this small abandoned town with a barber shop, pharmacy, and grocery store, to kept walking the railroad tracks until I came to abandoned park (Blue Heron Park? If I remember correct). All these abandoned cut outs of people waving left me a bit uneasy. I found a red, emergency phone attached to the bathrooms that were locked. I picked it up and sure enough it just automatically started ringing. It was 911. Although I probably could have hiked 10-15 miles back, it was getting dark and I figured I would ask for help. They told me someone would come to pick me up, and although I knew it would be the cops I just wanted a warm place and some food. As I walked out of the park, rangers showed up.
A biscuit.. the pumpkin spice variety 🎃🥐
